India Urged to Quit Assam

Guwahati: The United Liberation Front of Assam (ULFA) has demanded India to=
 end its colonial rule in Assam, holding its colonial policies responsible =
for the death of at least 35 tea plantation workers in Assam. The ULFA spok=
esman alleged that the both public and private companies operating in Assam=
 are exploiting the people of Assam in connivance with the Indian governmen=
t. Assam accounts for 55 percent of the country's total annual tea producti=
on of 823 million kilograms but food and medicines are a distant dream for =
the people with most of the families literally starving, said the spokesman=
.

35 workers on tea plantation had died of starvation and disease last week s=
ince employers; The Hindustan Tea Company, locked them out six months ago o=
ver a wage dispute at the Hatticherra and Subong tea gardens in the souther=
n Cachar district, 310 km from Guwahati.

"Up to 35 workers have died for hunger and disease since June with no sourc=
e of income, while hundreds of others, including woman and children, are vi=
rtually staring at death," said workers' representative K. Dutta Choudhury.

K. Dutta Choudhury who is the president of the Barak Valley Chah Mazdoor Sa=
ngh, the umbrella body for workers of 160 tea gardens in southern Assam fur=
ther told that at least three children died earlier this week due to starva=
tion and poor healthcare facilities. Disease has stuck most of the children=
 in most of the tea gardens in Assam with no healthcare facilities availabl=
e. Hundreds of children and elderly people in these gardens are passing ago=
nizing days with no warm clothes or woolens to keep away the winter chill, =
he added.

The two gardens, owned by a British company until 1970, had workforce of ab=
out 5,000 and produced an estimated 800,000 kg of tea annually before the l=
ockout. The Assam government did not take notice of the illegal lockout at =
the two gardens and even now after the incident it has not taken any legal =
action against the proprietors as yet.



