NSCN Accused of Violating the Ceasefire

     Guwahati: Security forces accused the National Socialist Council of Na=
galand of jeopardizing peace talks by violating a ceasefire in Nagaland.=20

"In a blatant violation of the ceasefire, the Isak-Muivah faction of the Na=
tional Socialist Council of Nagaland (NSCN) had attacked one of our patrol =
parties killing a soldier," said a statement from the Assam Rifles.=20

"There were several instances when NSCN cadres were spotted with arms outsi=
de their designated camps."=20

Led by guerrilla leaders Thuingaleng Muivah and Isak Chishi Swu, the NSCN e=
ntered into a ceasefire with the government in August 1997 to bring an end =
to more than 55 years of violent insurgency.=20

Despite the ceasefire, the NSCN continues to hold on to a substantial cache=
 of weapons, and its armed cadres reside in seven designated camps.=20

The NSCN, fighting for an independent tribal homeland, has held several rou=
nds of peace talks with the government in various southeast Asian cities.=20

The latest round of talks between the NSCN leadership and the government's =
chief interlocutor K Padmanabhaiah was held in Italy in November.=20

Nagaland chief minister S C Jamir also accused the NSCN of violating the tr=
uce. "Despite the ceasefire, the NSCN has looted bus passengers, fired on s=
ecurity forces, besides moving out of their camps with weapons, although th=
ey are not supposed to do so under the ceasefire agreement," the chief mini=
ster said.=20

On the other hand the NSCN spokesman has counter accused the Indian securit=
y forces of violating the agreement by still carrying out covert operations=
 against the organisation as well as committing constant human rights abuse=
s against the people of Nagaland. He also threatened to abrogate the agreem=
ent if India continues to violate the bilateral agreement.=20

New Delhi lifted a ban on the NSCN in November, 12 years after the organisa=
tion was declared illegal. The accusations of ceasefire violations come at =
a time when the two top NSCN leaders, who have been in exile for the past d=
ecade, are expected to arrive in India for crucial talks next month



